The RMP requires identification of possible worst-case scenarios which could pose health risks to employees and outside receptors if an ammonia release were to occur. At Buffalo Rock in Birmingham, AL a failure of the high pressure liquid receiver located outside of the building next to the evaporative condensers would be considered a worst-case scenario if a failure were to occur. This vessel has a volume of 60 ft3 with a maximum of 50% liquid ammonia at any one time, making a total release of 1,115 lbs of ammonia.  With a release of this magnitude the Toxic Endpoint is approximately 0.62 miles, which means the vapor would travel approximately 0.62 miles before reaching the 0.14 mg/L (200 PPM) level which is considered a safe level. The probability of a failure in this vessel system is very low due to the following reasons:



?    Industry standards for the manufacture and quality control of pressure vessels;

?    Ammonia is not corrosive in this service;

?    Pressure safety valves limit operating pressure in this vessel;

?    PM, inspection, testing and replacement of equipment is done by a licensed contractor;

?    Automated level control system with daily operational inspections;

?    Alarms are in place to warn personnel of process upsets; and

?    The emergency response plan and equipment at the facility.



The alternative release scenario for Buffalo Rock involves the failure of one of the evaporative condensers with a total mass of 659 lbs of ammonia (see PSI Traking Log - Maximum Inventory Levels - Appendix I) at 150 psig. The total mass was used to compute the release quantity rather than guessing a possible rupture diameter (therefore the total mass was estimated to release in 10 minutes). The condenser is located outside and has no passive mitigation. The facility is located in a commercial area with numerous buildings and a residental neighberhood nearby. The same procedure as the Worst-Case Release Scenario will be used due to the total mas

s being considered. The Toxic Endpoint for this scenario is approximately 0,43 miles. The probability of a rupture in a evaporative condenser is very low due the following reasons:



?    Industry standards for the manufacture and quality control of evaporative condensers;

?    Ammonia is not corrosive in this service;

?    Alarms for process upsets, such as pressure switches;

?    PM, inspection, testing and replacement of equipment is done by a licensed contractor; and

?    The emergency response plan and equipment at the facility.



The general accidental release prevention program and ammonia-specific prevention steps for the facility are located within the PSM, including Employee Participation, Process Hazard Analysis, Operating Procedures, Training, Contractor Qualifications, Pre-Startup Safety Review, Mechanical Integrity,, Hot Work Permits, Management of Change, Incident Investigation, and Compliance Audits. All of the procedures and requirements making up the prevention program comply with OSHA PSM Standard 29 CFR 1910.119, EPA RM Program regulations in 40 CFR Part 68, ANSI/IIAR 2-1992 Standard for Equipment, Design, and Installation of Ammonia Mechanical Refrigerating Systems.



There have been no qualifying accidental releases during the past 5 years as per 40 CFR 68.42.

The facility's emergency response program is based on the OSHA requirements for Emergency Action Plans (29 CFR 1910.38 and 1910.119) and HAZWOPER (29 CFR 1910.120). We have trained employees for emergency response and maintain a written emergency response plan. This plan is coordinated with the Local Emergency Planning Committee (LEPC) and the local fire department. We conduct annual drills for implementation of the emergency response plan at the facility with the participation of the LEPC and the fire department. The facility is equipped with a siren to warn the community of an emergency. The siren is tested monthly.

